= Catalan Political System

As of 2012, Catalonia enjoys a relatively high degree of self-government as one of the 17 Autonomous Communities of the Kingdom of Spain. Its political system is defined by the Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia, which was first approved in 1979 after the end of Franco's dictatorship, and partially reformed in 2006. The **Generalitat de Catalunya** is the institution governing it. Dating as far back as 1359 AD, it is nowadays formed by two main bodies, executive and legislative, with a separate judicial system under the Spanish courts.

The **Parlament** is the unicameral legislative body, made up of 135 members elected every four years through proportional representation. Catalonia does not have its own electoral law, which means deputies are elected based on the Spanish provincial system, following the D'Hondt method for seat allocation with a provincial threshold of 3%.

The (Most Honourable) **President** is the head of government, elected by the Parlament from among its members. The President appoints its executive council, which is made up of various ministers responsible for different policy areas.

The Generalitat's framework tilts slightly toward executive strength. No-confidence votes require an alternative candidate to be proposed, and the President can dissolve the Parlament and call for early elections. However, the legislative body has the power to approve or reject the budget, and to propose laws and reforms.

Catalonia has no special fiscal status as a Spanish Autonomous Community. Unlike the Basque Country or Navarre, Catalonia does not collect its own taxes. Instead, all taxes are collected by the Spanish government and then redistributed to the Autonomous Communities through a complex funding formula. This has always resulted in an acute deficit for Catalonia, with estimates at around €20 billion, close to 8-10% of Catalonia's GDP, or almost half of the Generalitat's annual budget.

With this budget, the Generalitat does have to manage its many areas it does control. These include education, health, transportation, urban planning, ecology, language and culture, agriculture, tourism, social services, and many aspects of civil law. It also has some control over internal security through the Mossos d'Esquadra, its regional police force, and its own prisons, with the Spanish police forces retaining fairly limited competences, at least on paper.


