= Political Parties

The Catalan Parlament is a multi-party mix where, with rising polarization, clear majorities are set to be the exception rather than the rule. The number of parties is higher than in most legislatures of this size mainly due to the dual polarization of Catalan politics: on one hand, the traditional left-right economic axis, and on the other, the union-independence national identity axis.

<span style="color: #002782; font-weight: bold;">CiU</span> - **Convergence and Union**
The center-right nationalist federation of the liberal Democratic Convergence of Catalonia (<span style="color: #002782; font-weight: bold;">CDC</span>) and the christian Democratic Union of Catalonia (<span style="color: #0052a3; font-weight: bold;">UDC</span>) has positioned itself as the moderately autonomist with pro-business policies force. It governed Catalonia almost undisputed in the post-Franco autonomy era, and has come back again in 2010 under <span style="color: #002782; font-weight: bold;">Artur Mas</span>, who has long championed fiscal autonomy. Nonetheless, the statute reform's partial rollback fueled internal debates on independence. In 2012, it faces strong austerity backlash and a voter shift to harder-line pro-independece options.

<span style="color: #ff8000; font-weight: bold;">ERC</span> - **Republican Left of Catalonia**
The left-wing republican party advocates for Catalan independence, socialism, and anti-austerity measures. Formed in 1931, it endured Franco's dictatorship and re-emerged post-1975. It governed in as part of the 2003-2010 tripartite coalition with <span style="color: #e73b39; font-weight: bold;">PSC</span> and <span style="color: #67af2f; font-weight: bold;">ICV-EUiA</span> but lost support after compromising for governance, poor economic leadership, and the failed new charter of autonomy. Now in 2012 is seems to be the main beneficiary of the growing independence sentiment, pushing for a referendum on self-determination.

<span style="color: #f6c300; font-weight: bold;">Cs</span> - **Citizens** (Party of the Citizenry)
The centre-right party is the most vocal force on unionism. Founded in 2006 from anti-statute intellectuals, in the 2010 election it managed to grow from Barcelona localism to regional lists. With a platform on anti-corruption, liberal economics, and a strong pro-union position, in 2012 it thrives on polarization and backlash against traditional parties.

<span style="color: #e73b39; font-weight: bold;">PSC</span> - **Socialist Party of Catalonia**
The Catalan branch of the Spanish Socialist-Workers Party (<span style="color: #e73b39; font-weight: bold;">PSOE</span>) holds a center-left social democratic stance favoring federalism over separation. Despite dominating the post-Franco era as the big alternative to <span style="color: #002782; font-weight: bold;">CiU</span>, its leadership in the 2003-2010 tripartite coalition with <span style="color: #ff8000; font-weight: bold;">ERC</span> and <span style="color: #67af2f; font-weight: bold;">ICV-EUiA</span> led to voter disillusionment due to poor economic management and the failed autonomy reform. In 2012, it struggles to retain relevance as the independence movement surges and its Spanish counterpart distance itself from any sort of further devolution.

<span style="color: #007fff; font-weight: bold;">PPC</span> - (Catalan) **People's Party**
The Catalan division of Spain's conservative People's Party (<span style="color: #1785cf; font-weight: bold;">PP</span>) opposes Catalan separatism and favores recentralization with free-market economics. Historically weak in Catalonia, it does have a chance to gain from anti-independence backlash, yet it is heavily hindered by the very unpopular austerity campaigns being carried by its own national leadership under Presidente <span style="color: #1785cf; font-weight: bold;">Mariano Rajoy</span>.

<span style="color: #67af2f; font-weight: bold;">ICV-EUiA</span> - **Initiative for Catalonia Greens - United and Alternative Left**
The green coalition supports left-wing policies, environmentalism, and a federal "right to decide" without explicitly endorsing independence. Formed in 1987 from communist roots, it joined tripartite governments pre-2010, gaining from 1990s green shifts. With vocal support for social justice and anti-austerity, its 2012 prospects are complex, as its pro-referendum yet not-explicitly-positioned on nationalism stance limits its appeal to both extremes of the national axis.

<span style="color: #C4B156; font-weight: bold;">CUP</span> - **Popular Unity Candidacy**
The far-left, anti-capitalist, eco-socialist platform demands direct democracy, independence, and municipalism. Emerging from 1980s local assemblies, until recently it had a strong grassroots focus and avoided institutions. In 2012, it is getting ready for its first elections, posing as the "left alternative" and pledging one-term mandates and anti-austerity. How much it is able to scale nationally may very well depend on its ability to remain internally coherent and united.

<span style="color: #000000; font-weight: bold;">SI</span> - **Solidarity for Independence**
The pro-independence transversal coalition sought sovereignty with progressive pluralism. Launched in 2010 by ex-FCB president <span style="color: #000000; font-weight: bold;">Joan Laporta</span>, it won 4 seats pre-2012 from anti-autonomist surge. In 2012, however, it is set to struggle against <span style="color: #002782; font-weight: bold;">CiU</span>/<span style="color: #ff8000; font-weight: bold;">ERC</span> dominance and internal fragmentation.


